,"start":196,"end":215}]},{"name":"796d","type":1,"text":"Additionally, as a mentor and teacher, I have found many other aspects that can radically improve the learning performance of developers. In particular:","markups":[]},{"name":"3004","type":9,"text":"Collaboration / pair programming","markups":[]},{"name":"2d82","type":9,"text":"Code reviews","markups":[]},{"name":"bd5a","type":9,"text":"1:1 mentorship","markups":[]},{"name":"10e1","type":1,"text":"If you want your team to improve quickly, you need to encourage those practices.","markups":[]},{"name":"89a3","type":13,"text":"Why Your Team Needs Strong Mentors","markups":[]},{"name":"e662","type":1,"text":"Some team members will be outliers in terms of their knowledge and their ability to craft architecture and set good examples for the rest of the team to follow. When they’re engaged in those activities, their contribution is a force multiplier, lifting the productivity of the entire team.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":227,"end":243}]},{"name":"87f1","type":1,"text":"In addition, these contributors will see more general solutions to common problems, and build tools that will help the rest of the team be more productive. (Other team members will, as well, but perhaps not as often).","markups":[]},{"name":"5c3b","type":1,"text":"On a team of 6, if 1 member is a strong mentor with a force multiplication factor of 2, that means the remaining 5 will accomplish the work of 10. You may have heard the term 10x developer. Mentorship is the most realistic way to make a 10x contribution.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":175,"end":188},{"type":1,"start":237,"end":253}]},{"name":"98ff","type":1,"text":"You may be thinking that my math is wrong now, because don’t the other contributors deserve the credit for their 1x contribution? Maybe some, but it’s not that simple. The real number of developers you need to help to reach 10x lies somewhere between 5–10.","markups":[]},{"name":"a879","type":11,"text":"","markups":[],"layout":1,"iframe":{"mediaResourceId":"d58f1a871d94048835b1fc5a784e22be","thumbnailUrl":"https://i.embed.ly/1/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Fpbs.twimg.com%2Fprofile_images%2F523508406548963328%2FtryZDeEs_bigger.jpeg&key=4fce0568f2ce49e8b54624ef71a8a5bd"}},{"name":"2793","type":1,"text":"Let’s dig a little deeper. This part is hard for many people to understand or fully appreciate:","markups":[]},{"name":"a850","type":1,"text":"A junior or mid-level developer may be able to close tickets. Maybe even quickly. However, the junior developer lacks the vision and experience to understand how technical choices they make today will impact the whole team productivity in the future. In other words, an unsupervised junior developer can be a fractional force multiplier, which creates a drag on the entire team’s productivity.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":212,"end":235},{"type":1,"start":309,"end":337}]},{"name":"2e68","type":1,"text":"Left unsupervised, junior developers will toss quick fixes in the general direction of every problem they face, frequently miss root causes, often cause regressions and fires, and leave heaping piles of technical debt in their wake.","markups":[]},{"name":"00e1","type":1,"text":"Junior developers will also frequently struggle with complex problems, pulling other developers away from their work to help out.","markups":[]},{"name":"5032","type":1,"text":"Mid-level developers (typically with 2–5 years’ experience, remember, this is what many bay area job postings consider “senior”) will come up with working solutions to complex technical problems, but those solutions will tend to be complex themselves, and hard for other team members to understand, which also creates a drag on team productivity.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":320,"end":345}]},{"name":"4877","type":1,"text":"Skilled senior developers will often come up with deceptively simple solutions to complex problems and teach other developers how to do the same.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":62,"end":98}]},{"name":"9abe","type":1,"text":"So, don’t hire juniors, right? Wrong. The junior developer may be very smart, and a very good learner. It’s simply a lack of experience and understanding that creates the negative drag effect.","markups":[]},{"name":"9f66","type":7,"text":"In a mentorship culture with lots of pairing and code reviews, even novice developers quickly become great contributors.","markups":[]},{"name":"9802","type":1,"text":"But hiring junior developers without senior mentors for guides is effectively synonymous with stashing time bombs all over your code base.","markups":[]},{"name":"6629","type":13,"text":"The Real Danger","markups":[]},{"name":"e9dc","type":1,"text":"When a development team encounters productivity challenges and large technical debt problems, it’s tempting to blame it on individual developers.","markups":[]},{"name":"e0da","type":6,"text":"“This one is closing 1/5th as many tickets as this other one, so clearly, that’s the problem, right?” Wrong.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":102,"end":108}]},{"name":"3e8d","type":1,"text":"The root cause of tech debt is a management focus on short-term, micro-productivity at the expense of long-term macro-productivity. When you let work byproduct pile up long enough, eventually it will clog the machine.","markups":[]},{"name":"a91f","type":1,"text":"Managers frequently make the mistake of thinking that ticket velocity can be used to judge the performance of individual contributors. That simply isn’t true.","markups":[]},{"name":"59b6","type":1,"text":"People don’t work in a vacuum. They work with each other. Your most knowledgable employees will quickly become the go-to mentors that everybody turns to with questions, and this is a good thing.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":173,"end":194}]},{"name":"393f","type":1,"text":"That mentor/senior dev is responsible for keeping the machine clean and well-oiled, preventing clogs that will derail the whole team.","markups":[]},{"name":"be72","type":1,"text":"But senior mentors won’t close a lot of their own tickets. Instead, they’re going to be focused on code reviews, unblocking the rest of the team when they encounter new challenges, and working to optimize the entire team’s long-term productivity.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":0,"end":58}]},{"name":"0532","type":1,"text":"The thing that engineering leaders need to understand is that your most productive team members are often the ones closing the fewest tickets.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":62,"end":142}]},{"name":"f2b1","type":7,"text":"The force multipliers on your team would be wasting their time (and yours, and the rest of the team’s time) if they were acting like individual contributors, trying to close their own tickets quickly.","markups":[]},{"name":"13a3","type":1,"text":"You don’t need your mentors closing tickets quickly. You don’t want your mentors closing tickets quickly. The last thing you want to do as an engineering leader is put pressure on them to do so.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":0,"end":52},{"type":2,"start":63,"end":67}]},{"name":"7018","type":1,"text":"You need them helping the rest of your developers learn to architect the app in a way that allows the team as a whole to maintain smoother velocity.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":98,"end":117}]},{"name":"18d8","type":1,"text":"Bay area startups correctly value speed and agility very highly, but they’re terrible at understanding how to build a culture where speed and agility naturally flourish.","markups":[]},{"name":"9171","type":1,"text":"They’re too focused on closing specific work tickets today to remember that it’s the culture of learning and mentorship that will ensure the long term health and stability of the aggregate team velocity & productivity going forward.","markups":[]},{"name":"0f9a","type":7,"text":"If you want to assess the value of a senior developer or mentor, instead of looking at individual ticket velocity, ask the other developers on the team how helpful that mentor is.","markups":[]},{"name":"0769","type":1,"text":"Another great way to verify that your mentors are being productive is to look at their code review activity. They should be conducting lots of code reviews full of great advice about how the code could be improved in material ways at the architectural level.","markups":[]},{"name":"e7d7","type":1,"text":"A hallmark of an inexperienced reviewer is one who is focused more on inconsequential stylistic issues (semicolons, capitalization, whitespace, etc…). A great mentor will be teaching timeless software engineering concepts, design patterns, and how to write code that is easier for other developers to read and maintain.","markups":[]},{"name":"fe05","type":13,"text":"Why Every Company Wants Senior Developers","markups":[]},{"name":"77db","type":1,"text":"Every company wants “senior” developers because they correctly believe that senior developers will have a better understanding of how to build an application that is naturally resilient to the changing requirements of the customers and product managers.","markups":[]},{"name":"16dc","type":1,"text":"Senior developers are naturally less likely to produce mountains of technical debt as they close work tickets, and most will need less hand-holding to get up to speed on a new codebase.","markups":[]},{"name":"551c","type":13,"text":"Why Few Startups Have Real Senior Developers","markups":[]},{"name":"83d7","type":1,"text":"Our standards for what we mean by “senior developers” have shifted over the years. When I was just starting out as a professional programmer, it was very common to see job postings for senior positions requiring a minimum of 5, 7, or 10 years’ experience.","markups":[]},{"name":"4913","type":1,"text":"Today in San Francisco, you’ll see similar roles listing a minimum of 2-3 years’ experience. Part of the reason for this change is because there is a shortage in the labor market for developers who not only have the requested experience, but also possess the knowledge and ability required to do the job.","markups":[]},{"name":"bd84","type":1,"text":"But we still have jobs to fill. So we hire people with a little less experience, give them “senior” titles, and hope it all works out. It won’t.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":135,"end":144}]},{"name":"c4e1","type":1,"text":"As I mentioned above, experience isn’t everything, but when it comes to the role of a senior mentor, experience still matters a lot. There are some things that nothing but life lessons will really teach.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":126,"end":132}]},{"name":"13b2","type":1,"text":"There is a really big difference between senior on paper, and actually senior developers. A developer in the field 3 years lacks the real life experience of building multiple production apps at scale. They simply haven’t been in enough roles for enough time to see it happen more than once or twice.","markups":[]},{"name":"5d1d","type":1,"text":"That means they don’t know all, or even the most common ways development teams get into trouble.","markups":[]},{"name":"dec8","type":7,"text":"You can fill an ocean with the things a developer 3 years in doesn’t know they don’t know.","markups":[]},{"name":"d40d","type":1,"text":"But we hire them anyway. Because they’ll do a good job at building stuff and fixing bugs, and that’s almost always good enough for a while.","markups":[]},{"name":"c2eb","type":13,"text":"Why Most Companies Struggle to Retain Senior Developers","markups":[]},{"name":"be56","type":1,"text":"As I’ve just explained, a lot of the “senior” talent hired in the San Francisco bay area is not really senior. They’re less experienced developers willing to work for much smaller paychecks than real senior developers, who in San Francisco expect to earn north of $150k/year.","markups":[]},{"name":"15bb","type":1,"text":"A developer 3 years in will feel lucky to be earning $130k/year. The median salary of a software developer in San Francisco is just north of $100k/year. (Note to outsiders, that sounds like a lot, but in San Francisco, it won’t go very far after you pay rent).","markups":[{"type":2,"start":153,"end":260}]},{"name":"c255","type":1,"text":"Many tech founders in the bay area are young themselves. When you’re young and free of attachments, you can afford to share an apartment with four roommates and take home a small salary while you hustle to raise funding rounds and hire other people.","markups":[]},{"name":"5c1f","type":1,"text":"It may sound insane to a young founder to hire an “out of touch” developer for the same price they’d pay for 2 less experienced “senior” developers, and it may sound outrageous for a CEO to pay a senior developer more money than they will be taking home. Young startups typically view a true senior developer’s salary as “expensive”.","markups":[]},{"name":"89ed","type":7,"text":"Ironically, what’s really expensive is running a team without any good mentors. Mentors improve the ROI of your entire development team spend.","markups":[]},{"name":"58c5","type":1,"text":"San Francisco company cultures are frequently geared toward younger workers, including grueling hours & frequent after-hours company activities, such as parties, dinners, drinks, trivia nights, ping pong tournaments, and bbqs. Employees with families often feel like they’re not part of the company in-crowds when they opt to return home to families in lieu of attending such activities.","markups":[]},{"name":"7636","type":1,"text":"If you want to better understand how to attract and retain great mentors, you should reach out to a good agent. Agents typically only work with established senior developers, and their full time job is to find ideal roles for senior developers. They can help you understand how to craft a working environment that senior developers will thrive in.","markups":[{"type":3,"start":85,"end":110,"href":"https://medium.com/javascript-scene/the-recruiter-plague-how-recruiters-have-broken-tech-hiring-b7de2897247","title":"","rel